> We love farro, a nutrient-rich ancient grain, for its satisfyingly chewy texture and nutty flavor. Beyond farro's bite, it's a good source of fiber with zero cholesterol and fewer calories per serving than white rice that'll keep you full and satisfied.

Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 450 degrees.

In a #medium pot{}, combine @farro{1/2%cup}(1 cup for 4 servings, be sure to measure), @water{2 1/2%cups}(5 cups for 4 servings), and a big pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil and cook until farro is tender, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> TIP: If you end up with any excess liquid, simply pour it out. Alternatively, if liquid evaporates before farro is done, add a splash of water.

Wash and dry produce.

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%13.4oz can}; thoroughly pat dry with #paper towels{}. Cut @broccoli florets{8%oz} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1/3 tsp (1/2 tsp for 4 servings). Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Toss chickpeas on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp}, @curry powder{1/2%tbsp} (you'll use the rest in the next step), @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Toss broccoli on empty side with a drizzle of oil, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on middle rack until crispy and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}.

> It's natural for the chickpeas to pop a bit while roasting.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @ginger{}(minced), @garlic{}(minced), scallion whites, and a big pinch of salt. Cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @cumin{1%tsp}, @garam masala{1%tsp}, @chili powder{1%tsp}, and remaining @curry powder{1/2%tbsp}. Toast, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir @tomato paste{1 1/2%oz}, @mushroom stock concentrate{2}, @water{2%cups}, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, and @salt{1/2%tsp} (for 4 servings use 4 cups water, 1 tsp sugar, and 1 tsp salt) into pan with aromatics. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to medium low. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until sauce has thickened and reduced by about half, ~{4-6%minutes}. Taste and season with salt if desired.

Add cooked farro to pan. Stir to combine.

Remove pan from heat. Stir in @butter{1/2%tbsp} (1 TBSP for 4 servings) until melted. Season with salt to taste.

Divide curried farro between #bowls{}. Top with chickpeas and broccoli in separate sections. Drizzle bowls with @yogurt{4%tbsp}. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.